         <h2>How the Weather in Northern Arizona became so cold on May 9th: The Expose</h2>
         <h2><small>by Erin Joan Stevens</small></h2>
        <br>
        <br>
        <p>Normally, the weather in May in Arizona is quite warm, especially in Phoenix, where it's really hot. Northern Arizona, not as hot, still enjoys warm temperatures. But on May 9th, it was so cold that it had snowed early in the morning.
            Not lost upon this was that Portland, Oregon, the second most rainy city in the United States (after Seattle) was going through a hot spell of 80 degree weather. How did this happen, let's take a look at the events that caused
            this massive weather shift</p>
        <div class='col-lg-6'>
            <blockquote>He (Uncle Mike) needs to go to a home.
                <footer>Dad, when asked whether Grandma needs to be in a nursing home</footer>
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p>it all started on May 9th, 2015, when one family, the Bodie family, made a trip to visit the Grand Canyon to celebrate the son Adam's 30th birthday. This might seem normal, but one event started a chain reaction of super cold weather
            in the hottest of states: Arizona. That event, a casual recalling of Grandma Beverly Bodie, and whether she belonged in the nursing home or if she should stay in her house. While Jennifer Bodie, the main messenger for her Grandma,
            mentioned that her Uncle Mike believes she belongs in a nursing home; Steve Bodie, Bev's other son and Jenn's Dad, had a better suggestion. "He should be in a home," Steve said of his brother Mike, believing him to be a better
            candidate than their mom. LIttle did Steve know that this would start a chain reaction changing the weather drastically in Northern Arizona.</p>
        <p>Because of this event, Jenn, the wild and crazy member of the Bodie family, asked me on the airplane, what direction the compass would point her in. The answer seemed obvious, however, nothing is as they seemed. Instead of a typical
            response, Adam told her "You're a booger picker!"</p>
        <div class="col-lg-6">
            <blockquote>You're a booger picker!
                <footer>Adam, when asked by Jenn what direction the compass on his iPhone gave her</footer>
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p>That quote it seems lead Steve Bodie to reminisce about the past. On the descent to Phoenix, Steve, looking at the rocks, noted "They got pieces of rock here," a quote made famous by Jenn years earlier. With these moments in place,
            the weather started to become different.</p>
        <div class="col-lg-6">
            <blockquote>They got pieces of rock here
                <footer>Steve Bodie, descending into the Phoenix Airport</footer>
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p>Phoenix, a normally super-hot city, became a mere 73 degrees, colder than much further north Portland. Zits started growing unpredictably and randomly, as Adam asked Jenn what else was new, all Jenn could say was "A zit on my ass".
            Even worse, airplanes started to shrink with no passengers on the plane. By the time the Bodie's arrived in Flagstaff, one thing was clear: Steve Bodie was the only person in Flagstaff with shorts. Stunning in 45 degree weather,
            a little snow in the morning, and a light drizzle not commonly seen in Arizona.</p>
        <div class="col-lg-6">
            <blockquote>I'm the only one in shorts in Flagstaff
                <footer>Dad</footer>
            </blockquote>
        </div>
        <p>It was thanks to these bizarre yet surprisingly linked events that the weather got so cold on May 9th, 2015. Fortunately, these events did not have in succession again on the trip; and the weather went back to normal: Sunny with a
            high in the upper 60s and lows in the 30s.</p>
